			<ns0:name>b...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/105678638446503189415/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">dorrendorf et al's cryptanalysis of WRNG:

http://eprint.iacr.org/2007/419.pdf
http://www.computerworld.com/s/article/9048438/Microsoft_confirms_that_XP_c
ontains_random_number_generator_bug

microsoft says XP3 contains a fix -- don't know if the fix has been 
independently verified -- for this bug.  however, systems before XP SP3 is 
vulnerable.

we can workaround this by seeding a forward secure generator from the WRNG 
and then consuming 128KB of WRNG output to force it to be reseeded.  this 
causes excessive load at startup, however.  it could be done in a separate 
thread (at low priority) so it shouldn't impact user experience too badly.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2011-07-29T00:12:47.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2009-10-15T23:39:46.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:status>Accepted</ns2:status><ns2:owner>
